Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{3}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting lid.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, pop the sliced peppers onto a #large baking tray{}. Drizzle with @olive oil{for the peppers}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until soft and slightly charred, ~{14-16%minutes}.

Next, drain the @king prawns{300%g}.

IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

While everything cooks, heat the @olive oil for the sauce{1%tbsp} in a #large frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the onion and season with salt and pepper. Fry until soft and sweet, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Stir in the @chilli flakes{1%pinch} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and garlic. Cook for ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the @red wine vinegar{12%ml} and allow it to bubble away until evaporated, ~{1%minute}.

Stir the @tomato puree{30%g} into the pan and cook for ~{1%minute}, then pour in the @water for the sauce{100%ml} and bring to the boil.

Stir in the prawns, @sugar for the sauce{1/4%tsp} and @vegetable stock paste{10%g}.

Cook until the sauce has thickened and the prawns are cooked, ~{5-6%minutes}.

IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Add the @baby spinach{40%g} to the pan a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste your sauce and season with salt and pepper if needed. Stir through the roasted peppers, adding another splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and share between your #bowls{}.

Top with the pil pil prawns, spooning over all of the sauce from the pan.

Enjoy!

> 'Pil pil' is the sound of popping garlic as it cooks in the hot oil, a key characteristic of this famous tapas dish.